    <p>
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    <definition xml:id="d_path_integration">
    <title>Integration of complex-valued functions</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>f\colon [a,b]\rightarrow \C</m> be a complex-valued function, and write <m>f=u+iv</m>. We say <m>f</m> is <term>Riemann integrable</term> on <m>[a,b]</m> if the Riemann integrals 
    <md>
        <mrow>\int_a^b u(t)\, dt \amp  \amp \int_a^b v(t)\, dt</mrow>
    </md>
    exist, in which case we write 
    <me>
        \int_a^b f(t)\, dt=\int_a^bu(t)\, dt+i\int_a^b v(t)\, dt
    </me>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <theorem xml:id="th_FTC">
    <title>Fundamental theorem of calculus</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>f\colon [a,b]\rightarrow \C</m> be continuous. 
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                The function <m>F(s)=\int_a^s f(x)\, ds</m> is differentiable on <m>[a,b]</m> and satisfies <m>F'(s)=f(s)</m> for all <m>s\in [a,b]</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                If <m>G\colon [a,b]\rightarrow \C</m> satisfies <m>G'(t)=f(t)</m> for all <m>t\in [a,b]</m>, then 
                <me>
                    \int_a^b f(t)\, dt=G(b)-G(a)
                </me>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
